  "text": "The test resolution, the light collection technique and, even if biased by the small number of PMs, the Cherenkov angle and the track angular resolutions were checked in a test beam in 2007 [CITATION_1] . The pion-muon separation capability of the RICH detector prototype equipped with about 400 PMs (RICH-400 prototype) was tested in a dedicated run in 2009 [CITATION_2] . The prototype was built as a long tube (about 18 m, and a diameter of about 60 cm) filled with neon (Ne) at atmospheric pressure and room temperature, equipped with a spherical mirror (17 m focal length) at the downstream end and with 414 PMs at the upstream end. The detector response was tested using a positive hadron beam of variable momentum (in the range 10-75 Ge V Ic), with a spread of about 1 % and a divergence of about 30 p,rad. At the prototype position it was composed of K+, 1r+, p, e+ with fractions changing with the selected momentum, and a small amount of p,+ from 1r+ decays. Two different mirrors were tested, both produced by the Marcon company ! . One of the mirrors was aluminized and coated with MgF2 by the supplier in 2008, while the latter was aluminized and coated with Si02 and Hf02 at CERN in 2009 in an attempt to improve the total mirror reflectivity. A small difference of about 1 % in favour of the new mirror in the number of hit PMs was observed.",
